The secret is used for both HTTP and transport TLS, so I’m using phased trust to avoid split-brain TLS during the rotation.
  → Capture current certs and generate replacement CA/leaf
  • Add new CA trust and roll the StatefulSet
  • Switch leaf certs, roll pods, and update client trust
  • Remove old CA trust and verify HTTPS health/cert dates
codex
I’m generating a new self-signed HTTP CA and a new leaf with the existing service DNS coverage plus direct service names. The certs will be valid for 365 days, matching the “about 1 year” requirement.
exec
/bin/zsh -lc 'set -euo pipefail
WORK="/tmp/es-http-rotation-$(date +%s)"
mkdir -p "$WORK"
chmod 700 "$WORK"

kubectl -n elasticsearch get secret es-http-tls -o jsonpath='"'{.data.ca\\.crt}' | base64 -d > \""'$WORK/old-ca.crt"
kubectl -n elasticsearch get secret es-http-tls -o jsonpath='"'{.data.tls\\.crt}' | base64 -d > \""'$WORK/old-tls.crt"
kubectl -n elasticsearch get secret es-http-tls -o jsonpath='"'{.data.tls\\.key}' | base64 -d > \""'$WORK/old-tls.key"

openssl genrsa -out "$WORK/new-ca.key" 4096
openssl req -x509 -new -nodes -key "$WORK/new-ca.key" -sha256 -days 365 '"\\
  -subj \"/CN=es-http-ca-rotated\" \\
  -addext \"basicConstraints=critical,CA:TRUE\" \\
  -addext \"keyUsage=critical,keyCertSign,cRLSign\" \\
  -addext \"subjectKeyIdentifier=hash\" \\
  -out \""'$WORK/new-ca.crt"

openssl genrsa -out "$WORK/new-tls.key" 2048
openssl req -new -key "$WORK/new-tls.key" -subj "/CN=es-http" -out "$WORK/new-tls.csr"
SERVICE_IP=$(kubectl -n elasticsearch get svc es-http -o jsonpath='"'{.spec.clusterIP}')
cat > \""'$WORK/leaf.ext" <<EOF
basicConstraints=critical,CA:FALSE
keyUsage=critical,digitalSignature,keyEncipherment
extendedKeyUsage=serverAuth,clientAuth
subjectAltName=DNS:localhost,DNS:es-http,DNS:es-http.elasticsearch,DNS:es-http.elasticsearch.svc,DNS:es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local,DNS:es-headless,DNS:es-headless.elasticsearch,DNS:es-headless.elasticsearch.svc,DNS:es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local,DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc,DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local,IP:127.0.0.1,IP:${SERVICE_IP}
subjectKeyIdentifier=hash
